The Job Market 2023.

Hello! Welcome.

This is a small data visualization exercise that explores the state of the global labor market for the year 2023. The data was provided by Amirmahdi Aboutalebi and sourced from Kaggle. It has a sample of 6648 people in different industries, and it catalogues their age, education level, gender, job title, salary, years of experience, country, race, and whether they are on a senior or junior position.

Exec Summary

  1. Men are still more represented in the job market. 55% of all entries in the sample were men while 45% were female. This also permiates to the 20 highest paying jobs, where 70% of all the workers are men and 29.9% are women.

  2. Top ten highest paying jobs are: Software Engineer Manager, Project Engineer, Marketing Director, Director of Data Science, Director of Engineering, Director of Finance, Director of Human Resources, CEO, Director of Sales and Marketing, VP of Finance. The salary distribution among these titles ranges from 50000 to 250000 US dollars a year.

  3. Among the top ten highest paying job, the first four also are the ones with the large amount of people in the group. While having 842 people in the top 10 highest paying jobs, 376 (45%) of them were software engineer managers, 317 (38%) were project engineers,65 (8%) were market directors, and 57 (6.76%) were directors of data science. The remaining titles had very few numbers, between 2 and 1 person in each title.

  4. Men outnumber women in each level of education in the top 20 high paying jobs while women outnumber men at two years of education level in the global dataset. In the top 20 high paying jobs, 10 years of experience and 3 years of education seem to be a sweet spot for getting a salary of 150k and above a year (US Dollar), while for the global dataset, the same years of experience and salary will get you around 100k a year. That being said, the more years of experience you've the better the salary becomes, even at 2 years of education.

  5. In the five countries from which the sample size was collected (USA, Canada, UK, Australia, China), the majority of workers in both genders are White and Asian (~30%, ~24% respectively). This character permiates to the highest paying jobs also, with 29% and 30.4% of males and females respectively being white, and 24.8% and 20.8% being Asian. This makes sense as 4 of the 5 countries used to get the sample are dominated by the white race, and the last country (China) is an economic giant with a very large population that identifies as Asian for the most part.

  6. Seniority is dominated by the white and asian ethnicities, which is to be expected considering the demographics of the data. This only changes a little bit when it comes to seniors in the 20 highest paying jobs who also have less than 5 years of experience. In that category, there are more white seniors, followed by black ones, followed by Chinese and Korean.

  7. Senior positions are also more accrued by men rather than women. This is in both the global view of the data and among the 20 highest paying jobs, years of experience being a likely factor. When seniority was explored against the number of years of experience, women dominated seniority below 5 and between 23-25 years of experince. Apart from that, seniority is dominated by men, with the exception of years 7 and 15, when the number of female seniors also surpasses the number of male ones. Another suprising finding in this section is that; majority of seniors in highest paying jobs with less than 5 years of experience are female. Out of 25 seniors that fit this category, only one is male.

  8. In terms of which jobs the seniors come from, most of them come from the top 5 highest paying jobs, with the exception of Human Resource Managers and HR Generalists. Project Engineers had the most seniors, providing 32% of all seniors (316 people) and software engineering (25% (240 people) departments. The remaining titles include: Product Marketing Manager (7%, 69 people), Data scientists (6%, 61 people), and Research Scientists (5%, 49 people)

# Let's get percentages of the data above.

males_highest_paying_jobs = highest_paying_jobs[highest_paying_jobs["Gender"] == "Male"].groupby("Race").count()

females_highest_paying_jobs = highest_paying_jobs[highest_paying_jobs["Gender"] == "Female"].groupby("Race").count()

males_highest_paying_jobs["Percentage"] = (males_highest_paying_jobs.iloc[:, 0] / males_highest_paying_jobs.iloc[:, 0].sum()) * 100

females_highest_paying_jobs["Percentage"] = (females_highest_paying_jobs.iloc[:, 0] / females_highest_paying_jobs.iloc[:, 0].sum()) * 100

races_highest_paying_jobs = pd.concat([males_highest_paying_jobs[["Percentage"]].sort_values("Percentage", ascending=False), 
                                       females_highest_paying_jobs[["Percentage"]].sort_values("Percentage", ascending=False)], axis=1)

races_highest_paying_jobs.columns = ["Males", "Females"]

Conclusion

  • Although the dataset is very insightful, it lacks the quality to represent the whole world in this matter. A dataset that had countries in each geo-economical income group would've been more accurate.

  • For the next uploader of this kind of data, it will be very helpful if one mentions the units in which their variables are expressed in, such as salary is in USD, or years of education as whether the university education or else.
